The drying stage of making a mug.
In my last post I did a little video of throwing a mug. I have a few more steps to go before these are ready for my holiday open studio on December 10th and 11th. 
Oh yeah, and there will be plenty of bowls available too!
The non-potter often thinks when they see a potter throwing a mug that it’s quickly made. My response is that this is only one tiny step in the whole process.
So what are all the steps to making a mug? Well here you go:
1. Preparing the clay/wedging.
2. Centering/throwing the form.
3. Drying to leather hard consistency for trimming.
4. Trimming the bottoms.
5. Making and attaching the handle.
6. Drying everything slowly over a few days so the handles don’t crack off.
7. Checking each piece for burrs and sharp high spots and smoothing out with a sponge or metal tool.
8. Loading and firing the 12 hour bisque kiln.
9. Unloading the kiln after 24 hours of cooling.
10. Glazing, which could include a few different layers of glazes, and sometimes spraying a glaze over the layers… ‘cause let’s face it, electric kiln fired glazes can sometimes be a bit boring.
11. Loading and firing the glaze kiln for about 18 hours.
12. Unloading the kiln after 24 hours of cooling.
13. Sanding the bottoms smooth so they don’t scratch your table.
14. Presenting the work, be it through photos online or a nice display at an open studio or show.
Whew, a lot goes into that nice handmade mug!
Potters out there, did I miss anything?
.

A glimpse of yesterday at my open studio. It was a snowy day, a much quieter day then the very busy Saturday the day before. I had some time to give demonstrations on how I create this carved pattern. This method is called water etching. The green pattern is wax resist. I’m “carving” away the clay, with a wet sponge, and a sharp tool to get in the little nooks and crannies. The wax blocks the water so the pattern stays put while the rest is etched away. It’s a very long slow process and I still have quite a bit to do on this.
It was so nice to see people at my studio this weekend, and to share what I make and how I make it. Thank you for coming by!
.

I quietly filled my online shop today with this and lots of other goodies. I say quietly because I’m not a big fan of the scarcity mindset… the big buildup to the “online shop update”, where people have to make an instant decision and click the add to cart button before someone else does. I personally like to have a little bit more time to think about my purchase.
In the past I’ve tried to think of the announced buildup for weeks type “shop update” as a show of sorts, and the people that come to the show get first dibs. Yet this model of the online show just isn’t quite the same as a community based in-person show, where there is talking, sharing stories and maybe drinking wine together. The online show is quite lacking, basically it’s just a frantic online shopping experience.

One of my goals for this year is to have work always available in my online shop. 
Yes I know that I am one person and my handmade items are limited because I can only make a finite amount of work.
It’s a task to keep work stocked in the online shop. There is so much to do with taking photos, editing and uploading photos and writing a description with measurements. Maybe if I do a little at a time rather than all at once it won’t be a full two day daunting task.
I like to think of it this way also… if I owned a brick and mortar store and the shelves were empty, what would a customer think?

Well that’s my thoughts on this. How about you out there, any thoughts on this subject?
.
#handmade #potterystudio #potter #sellingpottery #liddedbox #glaze #lucyfagellapottery #handmadeinmassachusetts

This past week I’ve been making all sorts of bowls and looking out my studio window at the beautiful snow. The third pic is at dusk on a late night in the studio.
Lots of trimming on these bowls. I really like trimming when the clay is soft, but sometimes on bowls it will collapse the clay wall a little bit. So I trim them almost to the finished point, leaving them some thickness. I’ll flip the bowls over and let them firm up a little more then do the final trimming and smoothing.

Butter keepers.
Dang, these things are time consuming to make. Lots of different measurements. You have to measure the outside rim of the form. The lid inside groove, so it’s nice and tight. Then the outside of the lid, so it’s big enough to carve the edges and so doesn’t look crazy big for the form. The flat lid could look pretty awkward, but you need it, that’s the part that holds the butter. It has to be easy enough to grab and flip over to set on the table. Then very important, the lid inside cup width and height so it doesn’t touch the inside bottom or sides of the form. 🤓 … every time I make these I say, I have to raise the price, and I do, little by little. I like to keep my work affordable for pottery lovers, but dang the time and effort that goes into these is crazy. 🤪Each one is a sculpture for butter on your table. 
Making these for the @asparagusvalleypotterytrail 🔸 … and if you’re asking yourself right now, how do these work? The room temperature butter goes in the lid cup. Water goes in the bottom base. It seals the butter letting it stay out on your kitchen counter for up to two weeks. Never having hard butter again! 😁
.

🌞Artist Spotlight: 🌞
This week we look at Lucy Fagella’s ceramic art. Lucy uses Liz’s Light for most of her work and creates all her own glazes with materials we carry at Sheffield Pottery

“I choose to make intentional slow pottery. I believe that handmade work is important in our fast-paced digital world. The marks on the clay, the glaze variations, the slight size differences from piece to piece are all reminders that it was made by hand. It connects you, the receiver of this work, to me, the maker.”
- @lucyfagella

What’s this?…
When you make long, narrow, flat bottom servers they tend to pull up in the middle and warp. Believe me, I have ruined many of these in the past. 🙄
I’ve tried different things to weigh the mid section down, and it seems these square bats are working the best for me. I’m drying them slowly which helps too.
Any of you potters out there have other tricks up your sleeve to keep these flat?
🔸These are the finished asparagus servers from the last couple of video posts.  After they dry for awhile they will be bisque fired, glazed and glaze fired🤞🏼 for the @asparagusvalleypotterytrail

Our sweet, sweet dog Daisy died yesterday. She was the whole family’s dog but had that special connection with me. She was my loving, furry companion for 11 years… not long enough. Daisy had an inoperable tumor in her diaphragm between her lungs, heart and liver. We’ve watched her go from 65 lbs to 45 lbs in 4 months. She was the absolute best trail dog, and hiked with me everyday. She loved to wade in the river, even till the end when she struggled to breathe… the cold water must have made her feel better. 
She would put her head on the bed every morning to wake me up and waited for me at the front door if I just went out to get the mail. She was also a good watchdog, barking at visitors briefly, then nudged them to pet her with her head up against their leg. If she really trusted them she would roll over on her back for a belly rub.
She was also the cutest puppy ever!
💕Forever in my heart Daisy May💕.
.
.
#mydog

The month of May has found me more on the homestead than in the studio, as May usually does.
I started back in the studio this week making mugs for a special order. Feels good to be back at it!
Honestly it’s been a tough couple of weeks after losing my Daisy dog. Thank you to all who sent me well wishes and so many lovely, heartfelt messages. 💕
I took my camera outside to capture some of what’s happening on the land right now. We had a hard frost last week, so we lost quite a bit of our fruit… pictured is one of the few pears that remain. There are no peaches whatsoever this year, we lost them during the -20 February freeze along with the bees. We purchased a new batch of bees and they are doing well. Pictured is some dark and light honey out in the sun. Raw honey crystallizes and hardens after several months, when you give it a couple of days of hot sun it becomes fluid again.
Everything else is looking good in the gardens, the chickens are laying tons of eggs, and the meat bird chicks will arrive next week!
.

The garlic is ready… the garlic jars however are not. Hopefully I will be glazing some in a week or so.
I love picking garlic and other root crops, it’s always a surprise!

On another note… my heart goes out to all the people who were affected by the flooding in VT, Western MA, CT and NY (Hudson Valley). The rains were torrential for too long.
It’s been a hard season for the full time farmers who depend on their crops for their livelihood. Some farmers lost 90% of their produce. 😢
Our land here has soaked soil and standing water in parts, but we don’t make a living from our crops, we just feed ourselves and extended family.

To all the farmers out there who feed us all, thank you 🙏🏼 …

Here’s the little salt cellar that I glazed from the last video post. Listen to the sounds of vitrified clay… like I said, in the video, us potters are so weird, geeking out on the sound of clay. 🤣…
This is some of the new dark clay that I have been testing. I won’t be giving up my white clay anytime soon, but it is nice to have some variety.
I’ve used the leaf motif on my pottery at various times through my pottery career, then get tired of it. I’m feeling like it’s time to circle back around to using the leaf motif in this way once again.
.

Butter keeper.
I’ve made butter keepers for over 20 years, and they are still the most complicated form I make, with all the measurements and having it not look goofy with a flat top. I try to simplify them as the years go by. I try to figure out a way that they won’t take as much time to make…spoiler alert, there is no way to make a butter keeper take less time to make 🤪‼️…
This is my latest rendition. I wanted it to feel more like one of my salt cellar box type forms, and then, surprise when you open it you find the tall cup to hold the butter!
I will only have two at the open studio this weekend because the other two that I made warped and didn’t make it to the bisque firing.
.

I took these photos last night around midnight when I was finally done setting up the studio for the Holiday Open Studio.
I forgot to take photos of the long work tables that were also filled with pots, (I made a lot of pots)! Today was a great day, seeing familiar faces and meeting new people. Lots of pottery found new homes! Thank you to all who stopped by and supported me. It really warms my heart that so many people know how handmade pottery can bring joy to your everyday life. Your support keeps me doing what I love to do, and keeps our local creative economy thriving!
I’ll be open again tomorrow from 10-4 with pottery demonstrations again at noon… Oh and that was fun today showing folks how I make pots at the wheel.
I still have plenty of pots left, with an 3x8 foot seconds table that’s half full with discontinued, experimental, and slight imperfections. 😊…
